cs.CG, cs.DS, cs.DM, cs.GT, cs.SI. 

The paper deals with geometric graphs and algorithms for finding spanning trees in them. This makes cs.CG (Computational Geometry) the most likely sub-category. The use of algorithms and time complexity analysis suggests cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) as another likely sub-category. The paper also deals with optimization problems, which could place it in cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics). The mention of bipartite and multipartite graphs suggests cs.GT (Graph Theory) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the mention of multicolored point sets suggests cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as a possible sub-category, as this could be relevant to problems in network analysis.
